replies.bodyText:
^ I do agree. I made this change in my own tests probably 1-2 years ago.
It's a tradeoff of maintaining two copies of a constant, versus keeping the constant as an implementation detail (private field access, etc.)
If the source code version changes, a self-maintained version in test would be able to catch it. But, if you just use the constant, you could have like:
@VisibleForTesting static final String GOOD_VALUE = "oopsActuallyBadPsych!";

If test still had a hardcoded "goodValue" somewhere, it'd catch it.

